@course

id: book:freakonomics-mdvr
title: Freakonomics
author: Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner
description: How unseen incentives shape behavior in places economists are not supposed to look.
color: #f59e0b
genres: economics, psychology
relevant_for: anyone, curious readers, students

@segment
Hidden Incentives
HI

@package
Three Things That Should Not Be Connected
Free

@text
The explanation we usually reach for about why people behave a certain way is character.
He is lazy. She is generous.
Character sounds right and feels right.
But when you look closely, character usually loses.
It loses to whatever tiny reward sits one step away from the action.

@text
A Chicago public school teacher in the late 1990s is being evaluated on test scores.
Her pay, her reputation, and her school's future depend on those scores.
The tests are multiple choice, taken while she is in the room.
At some point, a handful of teachers begin erasing wrong answers after the test.
They are not bad people. Most of them have been teaching for a decade.
They began erasing because low scores were punished and the risk of being caught was close to zero.

@text
A sumo wrestler in Japan is climbing the professional ranks.
A single loss can cost him income, rank, and eligibility.
Researchers studying 20 years of records notice something odd.
In the final match, wrestlers who needed one more win beat comfortable opponents at unusual rates.
The matches were not fixed out loud.
An unspoken favor system handled it.
The upside for the one who needed the win was huge.
The cost to the other was small.

@text
A real estate agent in Chicago sells her own home.
She leaves it on the market for 10 days longer than she advises her clients to wait.
She also sells it for about 3 percent more.
3 percent on a client's house barely changes her paycheck.
3 percent on her own house is a lot of money.
She is not dishonest. Most of her advice is accurate.
She just follows a slightly different calculation for herself.

@question
What do the teacher, the wrestler, and the real estate agent have in common?

answer: Each was responding to a small incentive nobody thought to measure.
consequence: Exactly. The system rewarded one outcome, while the person was quietly working toward a slightly different one.

answer: Each was committing fraud for personal gain.
consequence: Fraud is the strong version of the story, but not what is happening here. The agent is not lying, and the wrestler is not bribed. The incentive is the explanation, not the crime.

answer: Each worked in a system with poor oversight.
consequence: Oversight is part of it, but not the main part. You can add oversight and the incentive stays. Oversight catches some cases, but never removes the reason.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Behavior follows incentives, not job descriptions. Change the incentive and the behavior changes. Leave the incentive in place and the behavior will outlast any individual.
hint: Ask what each of them was quietly being paid for, beyond their official job.

@text
These three stories point at the same idea.
<c:g>Incentives</c:g> are the hidden engine of everyday life.
Most people do not respond to values or rules.
They respond to the tiny rewards sitting one step away from their decisions.
The teacher, the wrestler, and the agent are ordinary people.
They were placed inside structures that quietly reward one thing and claim to reward another.

@true_false
If you replaced the people in these three stories with more ethical people, the strange behaviors would disappear.

true: True, better people would fix it.
consequence: That is the intuitive answer. But the new people step into the same structure and start doing versions of the same thing. The incentive is still there.

false: False, the incentive would still be there.
consequence: Right. The structure does more work than the individual. You can swap people in and out, but the behavior stays the same.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Systems shape behavior more than character does. An ethical person in a badly designed system will start doing the same thing, quit, or be replaced.
hint: Does the goal you are rewarded for match the one that is stated.

@reflect
A small reward that shapes your day without anyone naming it: a quick thank-you email that keeps you checking your inbox.
A goal your employer states one way but rewards another way: quality praised, but speed measured.
A task you would do very differently if the incentive were reversed: fewer emails, but more honest ones.
